Its not too terrible Leetah.<br>
They even sell various kits that come with a stand with hookups for a propane tank(you would need to provide said tank), a pot that will hold a good size turkey, and all the accessories (rack, thermometer, lid...). The package I bought I got from WalMart for 50 bucks. I think they still sell it for that price.<br>
<br>
Anyway, you fill the pot with oil. Peanut Oil works best. Most pots that come with the kits have markers on them that tell you how much oil to dump in. In my 26qt pot, it uses 3 gallons of Peanut Oil for a 10 pound turkey. <br>
<br>
Light the burner and let the oil heat up to 325 degrees. While the oil is heating, you can prep your turkey. To avoid splattering oil all over creation, dry the turkey with paper towels on the inside and out. Add whatever seasoning or other stuff that you want to do and stick it on the rack that comes with the kit.<br>
<br>
Once the oil is heated to 325 degrees, drop the turkey in (slowly) and let it do its thing. I usually cover the pot so oil doesnt sploosh out. It takes about 3 and a half minutes per pound.<br>
<br>
Hope that gives you some info.<br>
